K39,41 Resonance Parameter Evaluation, October, 2007.             1925 1451
R. O. Sayer, K. H. Guber, L. C. Leal, N. M. Larson (ORNL)         1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
We performed an evaluation of K39 and K41 neutron cross sections  1925 1451
in the resolved resonance region with the multilevel Reich-Moore  1925 1451
R-matrix formalism. Resonance analyses were carried out with the  1925 1451
computer code SAMMY [1], which utilizes Bayes' method, a          1925 1451
generalized least squares technique.  Our evaluation incorporates 1925 1451
recent high-resolution capture and transmission measurements at   1925 1451
the Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator (ORELA) to extend the   1925 1451
resolved resonance energy range to 1.0 MeV with much more         1925 1451
accurate representation of the data than previous evaluations.    1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
The data include transmission measurements by Guber, et al.[2]    1925 1451
and Harvey, et al. [3] on the 80-m flight path at ORELA; total    1925 1451
cross section data of Cierjacks, et al.[4], on a 57-m flight path 1925 1451
at the Karlsruhe Isochronous Cyclotron; and Singh, et al.[5] on   1925 1451
the 200-m flight  path at the Columbia synchrocyclotron.          1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
Also included in the evaluation were the high resolution capture  1925 1451
cross section data (0.1 < En < 600 keV) of Guber, et al. [2] and  1925 1451
the older, low resolution capture data (0.02 < En < 10 eV) of     1925 1451
Joki, et al. [6].                                                 1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
We have included resonance parameters (RPs) in File 2, MT=151,    1925 1451
and the corresponding RP covariance matrices in File 32, MT=151.  1925 1451
The Reich-Moore format with LRF=3 and LCOMP=1 was utilized.       1925 1451
The applicable energy range is  0.00001 eV to 1.0 MeV.            1925 1451
The RADCOP code [7] was used to generate both File 2 and File 32. 1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
At 1.0 MeV the File 3 total and elastic cross section values from 1925 1451
the previous ENDF evaluations were adjusted slightly to join      1925 1451
smoothly with the resonance parameter values.                     1925 1451
For capture cross sections above 1 MeV, the previous ENDF K39     1925 1451
theoretical values were normalized to 0.436 mb at 1 MeV, and the  1925 1451
K41 values were normalized to match the data of ref [8] at 1 MeV. 1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
Since the resonance parameter representation does not include the 1925 1451
direct capture (DC) part of the capture cross section, the DC     1925 1451
component was included as  a "background" 1/v cross section in    1925 1451
File 3, sections 1 and 102.  At E = 0.0253 eV, the calculated [9] 1925 1451
DC  cross section for K39 (K41) is 0.80 (0.52) b, which is a      1925 1451
large fraction of the overall capture cross section of 2.10       1925 1451
(1.46) b.  The upper energy limit for the DC cross section is     1925 1451
estimated to be 100 keV.   Therefore, the "background"  1/v       1925 1451
cross section was terminated at this energy value.                1925 1451
                                                                  1925 1451
The following table gives a comparison of our elastic, capture,   1925 1451
and total cross sections for En = 0.0253 eV and T = 0K            1925 1451
with the corresponding ENDF/B-VII.0 quantities, which are based   1925 1451
principally on the compilation of Mughabghab [10]. The capture    1925 1451
cross section values include the DC contribution.                 1925 1451
The quoted uncertainties, obtained from File 32, reflect the      1925 1451
rather large experimental uncertainties in the thermal values.    1925 1451
